In this proclamation, President Donald Trump declares October 2020 as National Substance Abuse Prevention Month. The proclamation emphasizes the commitment to addressing addiction to alcohol, illicit drugs, and prescription medications in order to save lives and create a healthier country. It highlights the efforts to combat opioid misuse, including the declaration of a public health emergency and the signing of the Substance Use-Disorder Prevention that Promotes Opioid Recovery and Treatment (SUPPORT) Act. The proclamation also mentions initiatives such as the Drug-Free Communities program, the Rural Community Toolbox, and the High Intensity Drug Trafficking Area (HIDTA) Program, which aim to prevent substance abuse and support those affected by it. The proclamation acknowledges the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on mental health and substance misuse and calls for collaborative efforts to strengthen support systems for young people. It concludes by urging the American people to observe the month with appropriate programs and activities.